** DEPRECATION WARNING **

Oh no! The `leftShift` (`<<`) syntax I talk about at 1:55 is now deprecated! It'll be removed in Gradle version 5, so it'll continue to work for a while yet, but you should declare tasks like this:

    task myTask {
        doLast {
             println "Herp Derp"
        }
    }

Instead of like this:

    task myTask << { // Don't do this!
         println "Herp Derp"
    }

The code for this demo is in the <a href="https://github.com/udacity/ud867/tree/master/1.06-Demo-TaskConfiguration" target="_blank">1.06-Demo-TaskConfiguration</a> folder.

You can find the Gradle DSL guide entry on the Project object <a href="https://docs.gradle.org/current/dsl/org.gradle.api.Project.html" target="_blank"> here</a>, and the entry on the Task object <a href="https://docs.gradle.org/current/dsl/org.gradle.api.Task.html" target="_blank"> here</a>.

To learn more about the Gradle magic that allows you to omit the quotes, check out Mark's Stack Overflow answer <a href="http://stackoverflow.com/questions/27584463/understing-the-groovy-syntax-in-a-gradle-task-definition" target="_blank"> here</a>.

The task properties that can be set using the map syntax can be found <a href="http://gradle.org/docs/current/javadoc/org/gradle/api/tasks/TaskContainer.html#create(java.util.Map)" target="_blank"> here</a>.
